      "role": "user",
      "content": "it was cut off at the end there. you were saying resource exhaustion? \n\ncould it be out of memory or something like ephemeral port exhaustion? also, you mentioned checking the OS keepalive settings—is there a specific way to verify if a middlebox (like an intermediate NAT gateway or firewall) is the one actually sending the RST packet? i'm really trying to isolate whether the reset is coming from our instance or something in the transit path.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Resource exhaustion is a prime suspect, especially when things are intermittent. If the instance is thrashing—running out of memory or hitting limits on ephemeral ports—it can lead to the OS dropping connections abruptly because it simply can't allocate the necessary resources to maintain the socket state.\n\nTo check for that, you'd want to look at system metrics *during* the failure window. Check CPU utilization spikes, memory usage trends, and critically, the number of open file descriptors or ephemeral ports being used on the instance. If those numbers are spiking right before the error, you've found your culprit.\n\nAs for isolating the middlebox—the NAT gateway or firewall—that's where things get tricky, because they are designed to be opaque. You can't just ask the NAT gateway, \"Did you send an RST?\" You have to use tracing tools.\n\nThe best way to verify the source of the RST packet is to use **packet capture (tcpdump)** directly on the EC2 instance itself, *and* potentially on the network interface if you have access to the VPC flow logs or a network tap. If you capture traffic on the instance and see the RST packet originating from an IP address *other* than the",
      "source": "target",
